III. APPLICATION TO THE PANCREATIC
:-CELL

We now specialize our model to account for the experi-
ments of Plant (1988) on mouse pancreatic 3-cells, which
show inactivation of Ca2+ channels. Although there is
some evidence for two Ca2+ channels in rat /-cells
(Hiriart and Matteson, 1988; Satin and Cook, 1985), rat
insulinoma RINm5f 3-cells (Velasco, 1988), and HIT
cells (Satin and Cook, 1988; but see also Keahey et al.,
1988), Plant (1988) and Rorsman et al. (1988) conclude
that in mouse d-cells there is only one type of Ca2+-
inactivating Ca2, channel. To compare with Plant's
experiments on the /3-cell, values of the activation-rate
constants a and /3 were taken from the experiments of
Rorsman and Trube (1986). Single-channel currents
were calculated from the Goldman-Hodgkin-Katz for-

